am Goode]] (D)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|5|E}}. [[Edmund W. Hubard]] (D)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|6|E}}. [[Walter Coles]] (D)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|7|E}}. [[William L. Goggin]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|8|E}}. [[Henry A. Wise]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|9|E}}. [[Robert M. T. Hunter]] (Whig){{efn | [[Robert M. T. Hunter]] is sometimes called a \"[[States' Rights]] Whig\".}}\n* {{ushr|Virginia|10|E}}. [[John Taliaferro]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|11|E}}. [[John Botts]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|12|E}}. [[Thomas Walker Gilmer|Thomas Gilmer]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|13|E}}. [[Linn Banks]] (D), until December 6, 1841\n** [[William Smith (Virginia governor)|William Smith]] (D), from December 6, 1841\n* {{ushr|Virginia|14|E}}. [[Cuthbert Powell]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|15|E}}. [[Richard W. Barton]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|16|E}}. [[William A. Harris (Virginia)|William Harris]] (D)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|17|E}}. [[Alexander Hugh Holmes Stuart|Alexander Stuart]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|18|E}}. [[George Washington Hopkins|George Hopkins]] (D)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|19|E}}. [[George W. Summers]] (W)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|20|E}}. [[Samuel Lewis Hays|Samuel Hays]] (D)\n* {{ushr|Virginia|21|E}}. [[Lewis Steenrod]] (D)\n\n==== Non-voting members ====\n* {{ushr|Florida Territory|AL|Florida Territory}}. [[David Levy Yulee]] (D)\n* {{ushr|Iowa Territory|AL|Iowa Territory}}. [[Augustus C. Dodge]] (D)\n* {{ushr|Wisconsin Territory|AL|Wisconsin Territory}}. [[Henry Dodge]] (D)\n{{col-break}}\n[[File:27 us house membership.png|thumb|400px|\n{| align=center\n! colspan=2 | House seats by party holding plurality in state\n|-\n|{{legend|#00f|80+% to 100% Democratic}}\n|{{legend|#ff9|Up to 60% Whig}}\n|-\n|{{legend|#09f|60+% to 80% Democratic}}\n|{{legend|#ff6|60+% to 80% Whig}}\n|-\n|{{legend|#0ff|Up to 60% Democratic}}\n|{{legend|#ff0|80+% to 100% Whig}}\n|}]]\n[[File:John White.jpg|175px|thumb|Speaker of the House<br/>[[John White (Kentucky politician)|John White]]]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Changes in membership==\nThe count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.\n\n=== Senate ===\n*replacements: 9\n** [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]]: no net change\n** [[Whig Party (United States)|Whigs]]: no net change\n*deaths: 2\n*resignations: 8\n*interim appointments: 0\n*vacancy: 1\n*'''Total seats with changes: 10'''\n<!--\nSorted Chronologically by date of vacancy\n-->\n{{See also|List of special elections to the United States Senate}}\n{{Ordinal US Congress Senate}}\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Alabama|Alabama]]<br>(3)\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Clement Comer Clay|Clement C. Clay]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Resigned November 15, 1841\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Arthur P. Bagby]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| Elected November 24, 1841\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Rhode Island|Rhode Island]]<br>(1)\n| {{party shading/Whig}} | [[Nathan F. Dixon I|Nathan F. Dixon]] ([[Whig Party (United States)|W]])\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Died January 29, 1842\n| {{party shading/Whig}} | [[William Sprague (Rhode Island, 1799\u20131856)|William Sprague]] ([[Whig Party (United States)|W]])\n| Elected February 18, 1842\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Tennessee|Tennessee]]<br>(1)\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Alfred O. P. Nicholson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Resigned February 7, 1842\n| Vacant\n| Not filled this term\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from New Hampshire|New Hampshire]]<br>(3)\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Franklin Pierce]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| style=\"font-size:80%\" | Resigned February 28, 1842\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Leonard Wilcox]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n| Appointed March 1, 1842, and subsequently elected\n|-\n| [[List of United States Senators from Louisiana|Louisiana]]<br>(3)\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | [[Al